name: Vinyl stearate
Reason: The basic unit for vinyl stearate would be ethene, which has a melting point of -169.2°C. A vinyl group typically adds some rigidity due to the double bond but does not significantly alter the melting point due to its small size; it is approximated to have a +5°C effect. The ester linkage (OC(=O)) contributes to the melting point with intermolecular hydrogen bonding and dipole interactions, estimated at +20°C. The long alkyl chain (stearate, C17H35COO-) substantially increases the melting point because of the increased van der Waals forces as the chain length increases. Each methylene group (CH2) in a fatty acid contributes approximately +2°C to the melting point. With 17 CH2 units, this sums up to an additional 34°C. However, due to the presence of a long alkyl chain, which can create a crystal lattice more effectively, the actual contribution might be slightly less per CH2 group. Considering the entropic effect and imperfect packaging of long chains, it is prudent to slightly reduce this value to +1.5°C per CH2 unit, resulting in a +25.5°C addition from the alkyl chain. Combining these estimates: -169.2 (ethene) + 5 (vinyl group) + 20 (ester linkage) + 25.5 (alkyl chain) gives the proposed prediction.
